Pattern:
Centralized Emergency Override Drift

Systems marketed as decentralized often retain hidden emergency override authority that expands over time during incidents or upgrades.

Observed in:
- DAO-style governance systems
- early-stage DeFi protocols
- hybrid on-chain/off-chain governance systems

Behavior:
- Emergency multisig or admin keys are activated for upgrades or crisis events
- Temporary control becomes semi-permanent operational control
- Governance votes are bypassed for speed
- Authority consolidates in core contributors

Risk implication:
- Creates structural contradiction between “decentralized narrative” and “centralized execution”
- Leads to governance legitimacy erosion under stress events
- Increases regulatory and community trust risk over time

Frequency:
high
